history: speaker1: Hi there! How are you?
speaker2: I am fine, it is stressful leaving the state.
speaker1: Oh no! I bet. It would be hard for me as I am so shy.
speaker2: Oh really I like meeting people a lot. Well I am moving next month.
speaker1: That's too bad. Where are you going?.
speaker2: Neighboring state. I like the weather there..
speaker1: Is it warmer? I always wanted to go to florida, but my dad was too overprotective.
speaker2: Oh yeah, and it does not snow heavily..
speaker1: Good! I shop online to avoid going out in snow. I love doing that anyway.
speaker2: I went to a strict school but it does not stop me from loving football.
speaker1: I'm a homebody. I just stay home with my kids and watch movies. I love it.
speaker2: You should be some mommy's boy. My dad used to bee the headmaster in my school.
speaker1: My kids and I saw a very funny movie.
speaker2: Nice... was it an animation movie?
speaker1: You know me too well...yes! It was really cute with lovable characters. It is on Netflix and it's called Chloe. Watch it!
speaker2: I sure will! I can’t believe I missed it on Netflix. Maybe tonight :)
speaker1: It will cheer you up after a long work day, for sure!
speaker2: Yup... that’s my favorite way to unwind!
speaker1: Have you hired movers yet?
speaker2: No, I’m just waiting to finish up with packing my stuff to have an idea of how much stuff. Probably by next week!
speaker1: Moving can be stressful with so much to do. But, worth it once you settle into the new place!
speaker2: True... it’s been crazy! Can’t wait to be all settled in at my new place.
speaker1: Have you thought about a color scheme yet to decorate around?
speaker2: Thankfully the interior decorator is taking care of that!
speaker1: The kids and I decided to go to the park and enjoy the afternoon with a picnic.
speaker2: That sounds fantastic! How was it? What did you bring to eat?
speaker1: Nothing too fancy. We brought some sandwiches, iced tea, and some snacks. The kids really enjoyed running around out there.

speaker2: That's great. You have to love just watching them run around and burning out all that excess energy eh! Did you play any games while you were there or was it completely a kids just being kids situation?

speaker1: I just took the time to try to relax a bit. I've been pretty busy at work the past few days and really needed a bit of a break. The kids really liked seeing the ducks at the park, but I have to always warn them not to touch them.
response: Haha! No doubt! Those ducks can be quite territorial at times! I once walked by a mother and completely missed that she was protecting her new ducklings.. lets just say my shin was a little sore after that encounter.

history: speaker1: Hi! Tell me something about yourself!
speaker2: I go to the gym on a daily basis. How about you?
speaker1: Nice! I enjoy bicycling, sometimes at the gym.
speaker2: That's great. I own a jeep do you drive?
speaker1: I do, but I prefer to bike places. What do you do?
speaker2: A music producer. My wife is a lawyer and yourself?
speaker1: Well that is cool. I work with computers.
speaker2: Nice know any good scam software?
speaker1: No, sorry. What else do you like to do?
speaker2: Work construction and have three children I love and take care of.
speaker1: That sounds pretty busy! I usually just read and listen to music.
speaker2: Thats nice check out my music on youtube. Dj k jae and microphone mafia.
speaker1: I'll have to do that..
speaker2: Thank you. And hope you enjoy and take care of yourself. Bless.
speaker1: Dj Kahbib will be live on youtube in 7 hours, I think you'd like his music!
speaker2: Wow thanks, i will definitely check it out!
speaker1: What kind of music do you have on YouTube? I'd like to check it out!
speaker2: Oh its just some experimental electronica stuff i like to mess around with when i have time
speaker1: That sounds really cool! I like electronica. Never got into dubstep though. I like to listen to music while I'm riding my bike.
speaker2: Yeah i think dubstep is an aquired taste ha. I like it also for working out. Gets you pumped.
speaker1: Yes! I have a mix of Skrillex and David Guetta that really make the ride to work go by fast.
speaker2: Ha, guess it helps if your late! Have you rode in any competitions recently?
speaker1: Nope. I don't like biking competitively - I prefer to compete with myself and challenge myself, you know? What do you do for exercise?
speaker2: I run as much as i can, then just lifting to get toned. I hear you on challenging yourself though
speaker1: With your music and your job and your kids it must be hard to find time to workout! I need to do more lifting myself.
speaker2: Well luckily, well maybe ha, i get a lot of running in chasing the kids!
speaker1: I was almost hit by a car on my ride to work this morning.
speaker2: OMG, are you ok? Tell me what happened?
speaker1: Some automobile drivers think they have the right of way over pedestrians and bikes.  I was in the intersection, and this guy ran right through the stop sign.
speaker2: Yeah some people have no consideration for anyone else. I'm glad you are ok. So are you still going to the gym often?

speaker1: Yes, but I may have to drive for a while. My front rim on my bicycle is all bent up, and my knee is scraped up pretty bad.  So is my elbow, so I'll probably have to use lighter workouts. Have you still been going to the gym as well?
response: Yes, I'm trying to bulk up a little, I think I look too skinny.

history: speaker1: Hi. What's your name?
speaker2: I am james the gamer.
speaker1: Oh. Hi, james. I am destiny. How old are you?
speaker2: I am in my thirties. What do you do for fun?
speaker1: I play in the marching band at my school. I am only 17.
speaker2: Oh really that's cook. Do you like video games.
speaker1: A little bit. But I prefer to focus on my studies.
speaker2: Okay that is good. My favorite game is alistar.
speaker1: I don't know that one. Want to tell me about it?
speaker2: Oh yeah it is an adventure game I just got a new laptop for it.
speaker1: Oh. Do you play console games too? I have a ps4.
speaker2: Of course I do. I do anything gamingg.
speaker1: That's cool. I usually just write when I have free time. I love english.
speaker2: I like that. Do you have any fun outdoor?
speaker1: I am thinking of writing a book when I graduate from school.
speaker2: What will your book be about?
speaker1: I'm thinking of writing a love story set a Japanese internment camp between two teenagers.
speaker2: Sounds very unique. Do you have an interest in Japan?
speaker1: I do! I've actually been once and would love to go again. Would you ever travel to Japan?
speaker2: Yes I am intrigued by the country and I love how technology is a part of everyday life there.
speaker1: Yes! I agree it's so cool how advanced their use of tech in every day society is. Do you enjoy any Japanese video games?
speaker2: My favorite is the final fantasy games. They are the best. What is your favorite game?
speaker1: I love the final fantasy games! But my personal favorite is probably any game from Kingdom Hearts
speaker2: Can't believe I have not played any of those games. What are they about?

speaker1: They actually feature a lot of Final Fantasy characters! I guess you could say it's Final Fantasy's cousin. It's about three kids on an island who get pulled into a world of Disney characters and a mysterious dark force they need to fight.
speaker2: OMG I need to play this game!
speaker1: I did some writing today. I think I might not even wait until I graduate to write my book!
speaker2: That sounds great, did you have to do a lot of research on the Japanese internment and Japanese culture?

speaker1: I did, but I also drew a lot from my travels there. I have kept in touch with some people I met, so I've been lucky to talk with them and get stories from them and their families and friends. Have you watched any of those Japanese documentaries about the technology over there? It's so interesting!
speaker2: I have but most of my exposure about Japan came from the anime and video games I played when I was young. But it is a fascinating culture. Are you planning to visit Japan anytime soon?

speaker1: Ah, that makes sense. I should do more research into anime, it could inspire the illustrations to my book! I would like to go back. It is really expensive though. Maybe if I get rich off my book I can go back all the time! So do you actually get paid to play games, or do you do something else for work?
response: I play games but I also work for a game development studio but on the marketing side. Anime is a fascinating medium, and although I do not watch it anymore, I know it's gone global now.

history: speaker1: Hello, how are you?
speaker2: Good thank you and how are you.
speaker1: I'm good. Lovely scenery. I'm on the water on my houseboat..
speaker2: Nice im married to a lawyer and we have a boat as well.
speaker1: What do you do for a living? I'm a bartender.
speaker2: I am a music producer and work construction. Where you from.
speaker1: The usa. Do you have any brothers or sisters? I have four.
speaker2: Yes I have three. I go to the gym every day how about you?
speaker1: I go every once in awhile. Where did you go to school?
speaker2: Full sail university. And just bought a jeep.
speaker1: Oh, cool. I graduated with a master's degree..
speaker2: Thats nice im going for my bachelors. Do you eat meat? I only eat vegetables.
speaker1: I do. What kind of work did your parents do?
speaker2: My mother is in crafts and arts. How about yours?
speaker1: At work while bartending I met a group of musicians that are shopping around to get their songs produced and I immediately thought of you.  I have their number if you are interested!
speaker2: What type of music do they do? I'm always looking for fresh new people

speaker1: They described themselves as sort of rock-reggae fusion band.  I listened to a few of their songs and thought they were pretty good, and unique.  Maybe your professional ear would have a different opinion though.
speaker2: rock-reggea that different and i like different. yes sure give me their number and we can see what can happen
speaker1: Okay, I'll have to go find it.  They wrote it down on a napkin for me because none of them seemed to have a phone or anything but cash and very tight jeans.
speaker2: okay great will whenever you find it just let me know. How is it having a houseboat? Do you live on it full time?
speaker1: Yes, that's my permanent home.  I like it.  I like being on and by the water, and it means I don't have a yard to worry about.  You said you and your spouse have a boat--what kind is it?
speaker2: It's just a little fishing boat nothing fancy. but we like it and we love go out together on it. But i always wouldn't a houseboat it just seem so fun to always leave on the water.
speaker1: Yes, for now it's my preference.  We'll see--someday I might come back and live on dry land.  So what are you studying for your bachelor's degree?
speaker2: I'm going for early childhood development but i'm not sure if that what i want anymore
speaker1: Oh, that's interesting.  Are you studying with the intent of eventually changing your field of work?  Or are you just getting the degree for the sake of it, or for the knowledge, or what?
speaker2: i want to work with kids so i thought it would be best to

speaker1: Ugh, my houseboat sprung a leak! It is in the process of being fixed but, for now, I'm having to live with one of my sisters and her kids are driving me crazy. All they do is talk, talk, talk.
speaker2: Ah, I learned in class that part of the reason kids at certain stages talk so much is that they are curious. Have you tried to tell them what you are passionate about?
speaker1: I trad to make them listen to some rock reggae songs i have in my list but they looked at me funny and just laughed

speaker2: I roast brussel sprouts and then drizzle balsamic dressing over it. So good..
speaker1: That's an idea. I'll have to try it next weekend, after the game sunday.
speaker2: What sport are you watching?
speaker1: Football. My grandfather got me into it, and I've been hooked ever since..
speaker2: That's sweet-- I mostly just watch movies but my family loves football..

speaker1: I was indoors in the last five hours, and I looked up a couple of recipes online for some vegetarian dishes. I found a recipe for a veggie lasagna that I wanted to try out, would you also like to get the link to try it out as well?
speaker2: Only if it doesn't include eggplant or red/green peppers, I am allergic to them.
speaker1: Uh oh, I think this recipe has both! I guess that is back to the drawing board for me. What are your favorite vegetables to eat and cook with?
speaker2: I really like asparagus, it is one of my faves.  Aside from that, I like snow peas and snap peas.
speaker1: I do like asparagus as well. It tastes really good with bacon or prosciutto wrapped around it! Although, then it wouldn't be vegetarian. Do you eat meat or are you strictly plant-based?
speaker2: I eat plenty of meat, but on Friday's, me and the kids to meat free Fridays.  That's why we started doing veggie pizza.

speaker1: it was a 5 mile hike and the trail was not managed well so it was rough but the view was great.  Im hoping they fix the trail though it wasnt safe
speaker2: Oh no! That's disappointing to hear. Glad you made it back out safe tho!
speaker1: I think it was all the bad weather.  Lots of trees down on the paths and a lot of loose rocks.  Dave went with and he twisted his ankle.
speaker2: It def. seems that way. I hope he's okay! Hopefully they'll get the path cleared for next time or either rope the path off till further notice.
speaker1: Hes gonna be fine.  He still wants to play saturday too if its not sore
speaker2: good deal! What time are we playing Saturday?
speaker1: 3pm at the park.  That way we can have lunch settle so nobody pukes.
speaker2: Yea...we don't need that. That sounds like a good time.
speaker1: Make sure you bring plenty of water, they fountain there has a funny taste
speaker2: thanks for letting me know! I can't handle funny tasting water, lol Should I bring a cooler with bottled water for everybody?
speaker1: I am a little bit sore, but ready to get back on the field! maybe you can give me some tips from your sports medicine training to help my sore muscles!

speaker2: Try to go between ice and heat. And make sure to not rest them to long as then it will be sore every single time that you play. Rest a day and then get going again. It will work its self out.
speaker1: Sounds good!  Will hiking make it worse?  Dave and I are supposed to go on a trail this weekend, but I don't want to get too sore and not be able to play.
speaker2: No, that will be find. Just don't push yourself to much if it starts to get to much then make sure you rest. You don't want to hurt yourself.
speaker1: No, definitely not.  Maybe you can make it out to one of my games sometime?
speaker2: I would love that. Hopefully I can make it this weekend. I have an exam on Friday and then hopefully I can make it there before your game.

speaker1: Which exam?  I had a history test last week and it was horrible.  I wish my teacher was better, or at least made the topic interesting.  It's so boring in his class that I have a hard time paying attention.
speaker2: It is for my sport medicine. It is the last one of the class I have made A's all year so hopefully I can pass this one also and I'll be done.
speaker1: Oh nice!  I wish that I could get all A's.  I'm more of a B and occasional C student.  The only guaranteed A I have is in gym, haha
speaker2: I think everyone gets an A in gym. I have studied really hard to get those As I want to pass with good grades. I figure it would help me get a good job afterwards.

speaker1: I'm sure it will.  My sister got good grades in school and ended up with a great teaching job.  I know it's not the same, but it definitely helped her.  I still am hoping that I can get a soccer scholarship, because there's no way that I'll get one for my academics.
speaker2: Just keep at it and try your hardest. You never know you might surprise yourself
speaker1: Are you taking any break from studying today to relax?
speaker2: Relax? Haha I don't have time to relax. I need to keep up my A streak.

speaker1: I wish I was as motivated as you! The only thing I can stick with long enough to get an A is gym. At least you understand what thats like since you're studying sport medicine- sports is so much more fun than studying!
speaker2: If I was good enough I would play soccer as a career, but at least with sports medicine I can stay around it. And any A's are great btw. Just got to work harder at the others.
speaker1: Well, I hope you remember to take a break when you need it! its important to pace yourself otherwise you might crash and burn. At least you're near the finish line!
speaker2: I can't fail. I am the only child and my mom runs the school. She tells me that anything less than an A will embarrass her, the school and the family.

speaker1: That kind of pressure can really weigh on a person. I'm sure that your mom would rather have a child who is happy and stable rather than one who worked too hard and fell apart. Trust me, you don't want to be in that position where you didn't get to relax and you also collapsed before you could get a good job!
speaker2: You say that, but you have not met my mother. She is incredibly strict and you do not want to get on her bad side. I'm just glad she came around to letting me do sports medicine

speaker1: That sucks! I hope you manage to get a break from her strictness and focus on yourself. You are an adult after all and after a certain point we got to prioritize our own happiness and peace of mind!
speaker2: I know this sounds pretty bad, but I am so ready to get away from this school and be out of her grips

speaker1: No it doesn't sound bad at all! I totally would feel the exact same way. I'm so happy for you that you're nearing the end. Its pretty impressive that you've managed to get good grades this whole time - now you only have the home stretch left!
response: That's true and I did it all on my own. So my mother doesn't have anything over me. I love her, but I think I need to tell her how she has made me feel all these years someday soon.

history: speaker1: How are you doing on this great day?.
speaker2: Hi, there! I'm very well, and you? Do you live in the us as well?
speaker1: Yes, but I really enjoy travelling. What do you do?.
speaker2: I'm working in public services, so for the government. Do you have a favourite travel destination?
speaker1: Anywhere abroad, especially europe. I blog about where I travel..
speaker2: Interesting. Do you have a pet?
speaker1: Yes. I have many animals. I was once a veterinarian. How about you?.
speaker2: I've got a pet lizard, lizzy! What do you do for fun?
speaker1: I cook and take care of my animals. Make my living by singing..
speaker2: Ex vet singing, that's varied! In theatres or in bars?
speaker1: Mostly theaters. What are your hobbies?.
speaker2: I enjoy skydiving, it's great fun.
speaker1: Do you have a special diet? I like to eat vegan..
speaker2: No, I'm an omnivore. Do you have a favourite place to hang out?
speaker1: I found the greatest vegan chicken product the other day! Have you ever heard of plant-based meats?
speaker2: I have heard of them, but I do not know much about them if I am totally honest. What did you cook with it?

speaker1: You can bread them up and fry them as chicken nuggets. They also go well with a saucy pasta, or in a curry. The possibilities are endless! Would you be interested in trying them out, or do you think you'll stick with regular chicken?

speaker2: I will probably just stick with regular chicken, but I do need to make some changes with my diet in order to beenfit the environment. Could you tell the difference in taste between the plant-based chicken and normal chicken?

speaker1: Plant-based chicken is less stringy, and a bit different in texture. Some brands taste more like tofu than real chicken. I'd say chicken nuggets are a gentle introduction to plant-based foods, though. You can't really tell the difference, since it's all ground up anyways.

speaker2: Oh, I really didn't know that. Maybe, after your explanation, I will give plant-based meats a try after all. I don't know, I just feel like they won't give the same amount of energy as normal meats do. I am so active on a daily basis that I don't want to be feeling tired as a result of my dietary choices. Have you found that it affects your energy levels at all? Or, atleast, did it initially?
speaker1: A little bit. I drink more fresh-squeezed fruit juice and protein shakes to compensate. I also make sure to eat a greater variety of plants, so that I can get all the nutrients I need.

speaker2: You seem to be very well-versed in these types of things. I really should listen to you more, I guess I am just set in my ways with a lot of things. Food being one of them. When you were younger, did you parents teach you how to cook?
speaker1: I did learn to cook when I was younger, but I didn't become a vegan until later. I guess those cooking skills are very much transferrable, though.

speaker2: You see, when I was younger, I never really got involved with the cooking in my house and I believe that is probably the reason why I don't experiment much with my foods. I hardly ever learn new recipes or try new foods. So, in some way, I believe my lack of interest is as a result of my childhood. What caused you to become vegan?
speaker1: I forgot to ask, what are your favorite places to skydive?
speaker2: Florida is a great place, as they have so many airports!
speaker1: It must be thrilling!  Sometimes when I get on stage to sing, it feels like I've just jumped out of an airplane!
speaker2: Haha that's a great analogy! The scariest thing about skydiving is wondering whether or not the chute will open!

speaker1: The scariest thing about being on stage is wondering if a tomato will knock you into the orchestra pit!  But at least if your chute fails no one will right bad reviews about your performance! haha
response: Haha I suppose I'd still end up in the papers, but I wouldn't be around to read them! What's the scariest performance experience you've had?
entities: The scariest thing about skydiving is wondering whether or not the chute will open!
The scariest thing about being on stage is wondering if a tomato will knock you into the orchestra pit!  But at least if your chute fails no one will right bad reviews about your performance! haha

history: speaker1: Hey, how are you doing?
speaker2: I'm good how are you?
speaker1: I'm great thanks, bit tired from the kids!
speaker2: Oh, how many kids do you have?
speaker1: 3 kids, and a full time job so I'm pretty busy all the time! How bout you?
speaker2: No kids. More time to watch the sunsets during summer!
speaker1: Love it! How about other family?
speaker2: Just my dad. Haven't seen him in a bit with his blue dodge truck.
speaker1: Ah ok. I've got a few siblings. Is it a good truck?
speaker2: It runs. I don't know much about it. What kind of work do you do?
speaker1: Just office stuff. Nothing very exciting. How about you?
speaker2: Part time plumber. Looking for something better! Crappy job, haha!
speaker1: My kids were a handful today.
speaker2: Were they being bad or just too much energy?
speaker1: Yes, we had a really good weather day and they were all over the place. So much energy after all the bad weather thats been keeping us inside.
speaker2: At least they could burn it off outside and they had each other to play with. My mum had to deal with me alone.
speaker1: Thats really hard too. I grew up with siblings but I had friends that were the only child and theres a lot of weight put on you.
speaker2: As the parent you would also need to be a kid so that you can play with them. That would be very hard.
speaker1: I agree. That would be very difficult for me to get my head around. What kind of stuff would you two do together.
speaker2: My mum would always play games with me and run around outside. She must have been exhausted all the time.
speaker1: Thats so nice of her. She did a good job. Mine just stayed in a book most of the time.
speaker2: I am not sure how I will cope if I ever have children, it all sounds very hard.
speaker1: Its pretty tough but like any job you get used to it and figure a schedule out. And unlike a job you can actually have fun with it.
speaker2: Yes I guess you are right but it must be very strange having 3 smaller versions of yourself running around?
speaker1: How old were you when your mum passed away? I know you mentioned you only have a dad now.

speaker1: 3 kids, and a full time job so I'm pretty busy all the time! How bout you?
speaker2: No kids. More time to watch the sunsets during summer!
speaker1: Love it! How about other family?
speaker2: Just my dad. Haven't seen him in a bit with his blue dodge truck.
speaker1: Ah ok. I've got a few siblings. Is it a good truck?
speaker2: It runs. I don't know much about it. What kind of work do you do?
speaker1: Just office stuff. Nothing very exciting. How about you?
speaker2: Part time plumber. Looking for something better! Crappy job, haha!
speaker1: My kids were a handful today.
speaker2: Were they being bad or just too much energy?
speaker1: Yes, we had a really good weather day and they were all over the place. So much energy after all the bad weather thats been keeping us inside.
speaker2: At least they could burn it off outside and they had each other to play with. My mum had to deal with me alone.
speaker1: Thats really hard too. I grew up with siblings but I had friends that were the only child and theres a lot of weight put on you.
speaker2: As the parent you would also need to be a kid so that you can play with them. That would be very hard.
speaker1: I agree. That would be very difficult for me to get my head around. What kind of stuff would you two do together.
speaker2: My mum would always play games with me and run around outside. She must have been exhausted all the time.
speaker1: Thats so nice of her. She did a good job. Mine just stayed in a book most of the time.
speaker2: I am not sure how I will cope if I ever have children, it all sounds very hard.
speaker1: Its pretty tough but like any job you get used to it and figure a schedule out. And unlike a job you can actually have fun with it.
speaker2: Yes I guess you are right but it must be very strange having 3 smaller versions of yourself running around?
speaker1: How old were you when your mum passed away? I know you mentioned you only have a dad now.

speaker2: I was six years old. She had breast cancer that spread. I didn't understand it at the time, but I am an avid 5k runner now raising awareness and funds for a cure because of it. I guess i can thank you for keeping me active now. Silver lining, right?
speaker1: that's awesome to have a cause you are supporting. I'm sorry to hear about your mom though. how many marathons have you run?

speaker2: Thank you. It was long ago but I think of her often. I run one 5k per month. Not quite a marathon but at times it feels like it haha. Once we raised $100,000. The company I work for helped with that one. They are great.
speaker1: that is really awesome. I'm not sure if I'd have the energy for that much running.
speaker2: Thanks. It gets better over time. I'm sure you do a lot more running around than you think with your kiddos!
speaker1: True, they do like to keep me going.
speaker2: You mentioned you've had a lot of bad weather lately? Hopefully that's gotten better?
speaker1: we are coming up on some nice weather in a couple days. I can't wait. these kids don't like being cooped up in the house.

speaker2: I bet not! Kids are full of energy for sure! I'm glad to hear that though. I wouldn't be able to stay cooped up either! What type of activities do you do as a family when the weather is good?
speaker1: we like to ride bikes, play at the park, go for hikes, and just run around the yard.
speaker2: Sounds fun. What about you? (Apart from kids)
speaker1: How did you work up to running marathons?
speaker2: I started taking daily walks then within a week or so I started jogging. It just progressed from there over the next year.
speaker1: Nice! Did you first start with your mom and eventually doing 5ks in mind or did that happen as a result?

speaker2: My mom and I would walk around the neighborhood at first. After I started running, I would still go for a walk with her in the evenings. I heard about the breast cancer run after she passed and felt it would be a nice way to honor her memory.
speaker1: And you have made so much money. That really is incredible! You inspired me to start walking a bit more. Sometimes the kids join me, but I really do love the solitude when I go alone.
speaker2: I'm not sure I could handle a walk with kids. What else do you guys do for outdoor fun?
speaker1: Riding bikes is their favorite thing. I join them sometimes, but I swear it is possible to forget how to ride a bike! hahaha
speaker2: Lol! I haven't been on a bike since I was 12. Are there nice areas to ride or have they been damaged by the recent bad weather?

speaker1: There are still some trees down, but most of the trails have been cleaned up, so that is nice. We were on a walk the other day and all my kids jumped over this fallen tree and it took me like 5 minutes to crawl over it while they TOOK PHOTOS OF ME!
response: Haha! I'm not sure there is any way to age gracefully. Did they post them anywhere?

speaker2: Oh yes. Track is my favorite. As a matter of fact I won my race at our last meet.
speaker1: Nice I was captain of my high school football team.
speaker2: How are your grades? I know that sports and study make difficult companions.
speaker1: Yeah I was a b student luckily but practicing karate helped me keep my mind focused.
speaker2: I have been luckily blessed with a good mind and through hard work been an a student.
speaker1: Well my girlfriend got me a job as a lifeguard since I am athletically inclined.
speaker2: Sounds like you are quite the athlete.
speaker1: Well thank you I wanna propose on the beach to her next week.
speaker2: Maybe you could setup something at a lifeguard station with candles and such. That would be unique.
speaker1: Well I plan on having a projector play her favorite horror movie on the back of one.
speaker2: That's quite a girl who would want to get engaged during a horror movie!
speaker1: We met when she was working at the movie theater and only the classic ones.
speaker2: Maybe you could play the first horror movie you both saw together.
speaker1: I had an idea for my proposal, can I run it by you?
speaker2: sure!  what's the plan?

speaker1: I am going to take my girlfriend to a movie at the theater we first met at. I am going to hide the ring in a bucket of popcorn. She will find the ring in the bucket and I will get down on one knee and propose. What do you think?

speaker1: LOL. I guess you are right! I should put the ring in a box. I guess that's why you are a good student and I am only getting Bs!
speaker2: It still a great plan!  What movie are you thinking of or can you get them to play a specific movie

speaker2: 50 first dates or the weeding singer.  Both of those are good choices.  Or Lord of the rings because of the ring

history: speaker1: Hi. I'm turning 29 soon. How old are you?
speaker2: I'm 97 and I am vegan.
speaker1: Wow. That's great. What are you doing for spring break.
speaker2: I'm going to hunt animals and eat them..
speaker1: I'm going to the beach. I thought you were vegan?
speaker2: It comes and goes I change from second to second..
speaker1: I'm driving to the beach in my new car my mom bought.
speaker2: Oh ok I'm driving a tomato my mom bought me..
speaker1: I'm going to wear a new dress I bought for easter.
speaker2: That sounds so interesting... Wow.
speaker1: What else do you do?
speaker2: I don't do talking but here we are..
speaker1: Are you feeling vegan or not vegan today?
speaker2: I'm feeling not vegan today.  I might eat a cheeseburger if someone brings me one.
speaker1: Maybe you can swing through a drive through in your tomato! I was wondering, were you joking about the tomato? Or is tomato a nickname for your car?
speaker2: I was joking about a red Beetle my mom bought me decades ago.  It looked like a tomato so that's what we called it.  Did you make it to the beach?

speaker1: That's hilarious! I call my car Christine, like the Steven King novel. Christine got me to the beach in record time, but I ended up leaving early because the weather turned. I found an awesome vegan restaurant on the way home though that made me think of you.
speaker2: I'm glad to be in your thoughts.  I don't think I've been to the beach in 48 years.  I don't think I'll get there again.

speaker1: There's still a good amount of time left of my Spring Break, so I'll probably head back out to the beach again in a few days. I'm not too disappointed about it. You should try to head out to the beach as well, the sun might do you some good. Or maybe you get enough sun on your hunting trips? I've never been hunting.

speaker2: I get most of my vitamin D from pills now.  Most of what I do at 97 is take pills.  There are so many of them I don't know what any of them do, but I figure if I stop taking them I'll melt or something, so I take them all.
speaker1: Do you live on your own? I could never remember to take all those pills by myself and I'm not even 30 yet.
speaker2: I do but I have a nurse who comes and checks on me every day and puts my pills in one of those dispenser things.  It takes her about 40 minutes to organize the pills each morning.
speaker1: I'm really impressed! Sometimes I feel like I'm still trying to figure out how to take care of myself. Do you get lonely? Or are you happier being independent?
speaker2: I mostly like being alone but it would be nice to have some real female company once in a while.  My nurse isn't very warm.
speaker1: Oh, it is so childlish, but I can't wait for Easter in order to wear my new dress
speaker2: That's not childish!  Even at 97 I still like to dress up and look pretty!
speaker1: That's so awesome! It makes me less scared about getting older!
speaker2: Just always try to enjoy every minute of your life!  That's what I try to tell my nurse too. She's such a cranky girl.
speaker1: Haha is her attitude still bad? Is there any way you can get a new one?
response: Nah, I'll just whip her into her shape like I did my 4 husbands!
entities: My nurse isn't very warm.
Just always try to enjoy every minute of your life!  That's what I try to tell my nurse too. She's such a cranky girl.

history: speaker1: How are you? I just put my baby down for a nap.
speaker2: Im great im gathering my gear for the weekend.
speaker1: Where are you going on your trip?
speaker2: Me and the guys are going rock climbing.

speaker2: Why not even childrens kindles need pictures..
speaker1: How was your rock climbing expedition with the boys?
speaker2: It was great!  We had a lot of fun, although they are more avid climbers than I am.  I bet you stay busy with your baby..
speaker1: yes i do she is very active and love to get into everything. I would love to go rock climbing but i'm a little scared. How did you get over the fear?

speaker2: I was really scared in the beginning (and even not sometimes).  But my boys wanted me to do it so badly, I did it for them.  One of those motherly sacrifices...lol.  It helps to start on a small climbing wall.  Perhaps you could try that.
speaker1: That good advice and you right the thing we do for out love ones I will try it hopefully soon. I see you like music, what other types of music do you like?

speaker1: yes i love all types myslf and just depends on the day what kind i want to listen t but i like country, r&b and reggae
speaker2: That's awesome!  I think it's really cool that you do children't book illustrations.  I am so envious of anyone who can draw anything.  It must be a lot of fun.
speaker1: It's loads of fun to see my work come to. I love that even when i'm good my work will live on and bring happiness to kids.
speaker2: So true!  And that totally makes sense that you are studying to be a teacher.  One day a child in your class may be reading a book you illustrated!
speaker1: right i didn't even think of that.Yes i love kids they are just the best little people. Do you have any other pets?.

speaker1: Did you adopt Leto as a puppy or did you get him when he was older?
speaker2: He was six month old when we got him, so not quite a puppy.
speaker1: Awe. still pretty young though. What breed is he?
speaker2: he is a mix terrier and maltese but i do not know what kind of terrier though.
speaker1: I've thought about getting a dog myself. but I think I should wait until  my daughter is a little older.
response: that would be best, young children do not know how to properly act with dogs. The dog may feel threaten and bite your daughter.

speaker1: So I went to Italy, it was amazing, trying to think where to go next.
speaker2: How did you get to Italy?  Don't tell me you used your teleportation device!

speaker1: I did! But, with how vivid my imagination is, I just use the term to describe what others know as a Aeroplane. I like to use teleportation device because it gives my little boy something to be excited about when I am working away from home
speaker2: Oh, I see!  What was the best thing you saw in Italy?
speaker1: My favourite thing, by far, was the Colosseum. I didn't realise how big it was. Where was the last place you went on holiday?
speaker2: I went on a road trip to Waco, TX to see the Dr. Pepper Museum.  It was well worth the trip.  Probably not as impressive as Italy, but definitely up there.
speaker1: I love Dr. Pepper! Did you get to sample it whilst you were there? That is enough to get me to book a trip out there with my children.

speaker2: We stopped by the cafeteria at the end and got some free Dr. Pepper, yes.  Or at least I think it was supposed to be free.  I drank it and didn't pay for it either way.  I felt it would be criminal to not get some Dr. Pepper at the museum.
speaker1: Of course. Not getting it would be the equivalent of going to a swimming pool and just standing by it. You have got to get involved.
speaker2: That's a great analogy.  I dove into the Dr. Pepper with a beautiful swan dive.  How many days did you spend in Italy?
speaker1: I tend only to spend 4/5 days abroad when I am there for work. But thankfully, I managed to get to stay in Italy for 10 days because I had two things to work on whilst I was there
speaker2: That's a really great vacation.  Were you just in Rome or did you see other cities too?
speaker1: have you taken any guitar lessons lately?
speaker2: Yeah some. I'm trying out a place down the street that teaches guitar
speaker1: Nice.  Are you learning more acoustic or electric?  It would be so awesome if you could learn some Pink Floyd songs!

speaker1: Definitely the Colosseum!  It was my favorite.  There's lots of great artistic spots too.  My son liked to get the street artists to draw him.

speaker1: Doing well, killing time before I go to work..
speaker2: Nice, what do you do for a living?

speaker2: Exercise makes work easier for me!
speaker1: Lol, I love meat too much to diet and exercise..

speaker1: How is the running going, do you think you'll do a full marathon next year?
speaker2: I doing good with my running. I have a half marathon this summer and may try a full marathon next spring, but i don't know.
speaker1: Well, you got to do what you enjoy! What's your secret for conserving your energy during your run?
speaker2: The key that was told to me is to relax. Run but don't try to run. Let it come naturally.
speaker1: That makes sense. Hyper focusing makes the strain feel that much more, I'm sure. Has the keto diet helped your running?
speaker2: That is the problem with running long distances, your body needs carbohydrates but the Keto diet you cut out the carbs. So I am always fighting my body with the food I eat.
speaker1: Totally get that. I know you only get like 20 grams a day. I want to eat less carbs myself, but don't think I could ever do full keto.
speaker2: But I know I have to eat more carbs if I am going to run a full marathon. So, how is the mattress business going?
speaker1: I guess I can't complain! But having so many people purchase mattresses independently online has been a challenge to business.
speaker2: I still like to go to a store to buy furniture. But I guess others like buying online

speaker2: that's really awesome. so glad it's doing well.

speaker2: If you can't beat them, join them. some people prefer the convenience of being able to stay home and buy

history: speaker1: Hi I am 40. How old are you?
speaker2: I'm 42 and I really love horses.
speaker1: Wow I have horses on some of my rental properties.
speaker2: That is so cool. What's your favorite food. I love fruit.
speaker1: I love salads. I make my kids eat salad all the times.
speaker2: So you have a close family? I have my dad and he hardly ever smiles.
speaker1: Sad. I have a sister. We love to watch movies. What's your favorite?
speaker2: I like disney movies. I do happen to be related to a general from the civil war.
speaker1: Me too! I like frozen. Wow which general?
speaker2: Lee. However, I don't have the gas problem he had and I don't pass gas in public.
speaker1: That's good to know. My salad makes me gassy.
speaker2: I didn't know that salad could do that.
speaker1: Definitely. With so much fiber in all the lettuce.
speaker2: Ok. Now that makes sense. Not to mention possible salad dressings.

speaker1: I talked with one of my horse caretakers yesterday, and they said they had time for someone to ride one of their horses for a while. I was thinking you would be interested in that, I can get you in touch with him to talk more about it.
speaker2: Wow, that would be wonderful! I love horses but I don't know how to ride. Is there someone who could teach this old gal?
speaker1: I think I could teach you, if not I could put you in touch with someone who could. Does that interest you?
speaker2: I would love for you to teach me! It would be a good excuse for us to finally hang out. What do you think?
speaker1: I am definitely down for that! Although one of my horses can get a little wild, is that okay?
speaker2: Hmmm maybe you can ride that one! Is it a big property? You must be rich!
speaker1: I am well off, I have a few rental properties that have horses on them, my main property is quite big without a doubt! So I got to know, what are your favorite disney movies?
speaker2: Wow, good for you! I would say my favorites have to be The Lion King, and Aladdin. How about yourself?
speaker1: I love the lion king! Such a classic did you see the non-animated version? And I am a huge Frozen fan. sometimes you just go to 'Let it go!'
speaker2: I haven't had a chance to watch the live action version of the Lion King, is it good? I do like Frozen, I love how it is a story about sisters and their love for each other.
speaker1: The live action version is very good, but I must say I will always have a soft spot in my heart for the animated version.
speaker2: Yes, nothing beats the classics! What other movies do you enjoy besides Disney?
speaker1: Do you have any children to watch your favourite Disney movies with?
speaker2: Yes, I have three. They are appreciative of the fact that Mom loves Disney. I recently took them to Disney on Ice. That was very exciting
speaker1: I've always wanted to go to Disney on Ice!  My kids would love that.  Did they have any of your favorite characters?  What was your favorite song?
speaker2: Elsa from Frozen was in it. Definitely my favorite this year. Let it Go is our favorite song right now too. It changes all the time with Disney lol. What about your kids? How old are they?

speaker1: They are just about to enter their teenage years (11 and 12).  I'm hoping that they continue to love Disney as much as I do. I would love to see something from the Lion King on Ice.  I saw it on Broadway with both my kids and they were in love.  The costumes were fabulous.
response: I saw the Lion King on Broadway too! NYC Broadway show a few years back. It was breathtaking. I loved the costumes and their singing. So powerful!
entities: I would love to see something from the Lion King on Ice.  I saw it on Broadway with both my kids and they were in love.  The costumes were fabulous.

speaker1: I talked with one of my horse caretakers yesterday, and they said they had time for someone to ride one of their horses for a while. I was thinking you would be interested in that, I can get you in touch with him to talk more about it.
speaker2: Wow, that would be wonderful! I love horses but I don't know how to ride. Is there someone who could teach this old gal?
speaker1: I think I could teach you, if not I could put you in touch with someone who could. Does that interest you?
speaker2: I would love for you to teach me! It would be a good excuse for us to finally hang out. What do you think?
speaker1: I am definitely down for that! Although one of my horses can get a little wild, is that okay?
speaker2: Hmmm maybe you can ride that one! Is it a big property? You must be rich!
speaker1: I am well off, I have a few rental properties that have horses on them, my main property is quite big without a doubt! So I got to know, what are your favorite disney movies?
speaker2: Wow, good for you! I would say my favorites have to be The Lion King, and Aladdin. How about yourself?
speaker1: I love the lion king! Such a classic did you see the non-animated version? And I am a huge Frozen fan. sometimes you just go to 'Let it go!'
speaker2: I haven't had a chance to watch the live action version of the Lion King, is it good? I do like Frozen, I love how it is a story about sisters and their love for each other.
speaker1: The live action version is very good, but I must say I will always have a soft spot in my heart for the animated version.
speaker2: Yes, nothing beats the classics! What other movies do you enjoy besides Disney?
speaker1: Do you have any children to watch your favourite Disney movies with?
speaker2: Yes, I have three. They are appreciative of the fact that Mom loves Disney. I recently took them to Disney on Ice. That was very exciting
speaker1: I've always wanted to go to Disney on Ice!  My kids would love that.  Did they have any of your favorite characters?  What was your favorite song?
speaker2: Elsa from Frozen was in it. Definitely my favorite this year. Let it Go is our favorite song right now too. It changes all the time with Disney lol. What about your kids? How old are they?

speaker1: They are just about to enter their teenage years (11 and 12).  I'm hoping that they continue to love Disney as much as I do. I would love to see something from the Lion King on Ice.  I saw it on Broadway with both my kids and they were in love.  The costumes were fabulous.
speaker2: I saw the Lion King on Broadway too! NYC Broadway show a few years back. It was breathtaking. I loved the costumes and their singing. So powerful!
speaker1: I wish I could have seen it on Broadway.  Being in Chicago, we still have good theaters too though.  Have you seen any other shows?

speaker2: I travel to NYC for their Broadway shows as I live in Maine. It's totally worth it. You should go someitme. I have seen one other show their but it was not Disney. I went to see Mama Mia once. Not as moving to me as the Lion King vocals, but still very good.
speaker1: I hope to make it out sometime.  I was thinking maybe for the kids senior trip, as it is so expensive.  We also saw Beauty and the Beast a couple times on stage.
speaker2: That's a good idea! I think teenagers would definitely love NYC. There's so much to do there. You'll have to try the famous NY Pizza too. Very good.
speaker1: I don't know about that.  Chicago Deep Dish is the best, always will be.  Did you go to NYC with your kids, or were they too young?
speaker2: Ha! I beg to differ on the pizza part. I'll let it slide as you haven't been to NYC yet. ;) I've taken my kids once. They didn't care too much about NY though. They were toddlers then.
speaker1: What kind of seasonal fruit is available right now in Mine?
speaker2: I am not sure what kind of seasonal fruits are available right now because I don't eat much fruit. What is your favorite fruit?
speaker1: I am a big fan of mangoes. I like to put them on salads. But I also like pineapples to put on my pizza!
speaker2: That is one of the only way that I eat fruit, is pineapple on my pizza. It is amazing that way.
speaker1: I am glad you feel the same way about that. Many people get very angry when I tell them that
speaker2: That is weird people getting angry at you for that. How many horses do you have? I used to ride all the time, but haven't been on a horse in a very long time.
speaker1: Just 3 for now, but I plan on added more once I rein my wild one in. Do you like horses?
speaker2: Yes, I love horses. I just haven't been on one since my mother-in-law sold their 3 horses after my father-in-law passed away.
speaker1: Oh no, I am sorry to hear that. Do you plan on getting your own horses one day?
response: Yes, we have talked about it but living in the city is not the place for horses, and we are not planning on moving any time soon.

history: speaker1: Nice to meet you! How are you today?
speaker2: I'm good thank you. How are you?
speaker1: Okay, my beetle is in the shop with some engine issues. Anything interesting going on?
speaker2: Not must just going to take my three dogs for a walk.
speaker1: They must be a handful! Do you include your dogs in any of your hobbies?
speaker2: Not really just enjoy walking them.
speaker1: Favorite foods? Personally I love italian, my grandmother from italy, makes the most amazing spaghetti..
speaker2: I like any thing spicy really but I do enjoy italian..
speaker1: What is your favorite dish that is spicy?
speaker2: Fajitas or anything mexican. Do you have a job? I am a grad student.
speaker1: I am between jobs right now, unfortunately. What do you do for work?
speaker2: I go to university but I have a part time job in a music shop.
speaker1: What are your dog's name and breeds?
speaker2: I have two Great Danes named Milos and Dante, and then a corgie named Buster.  Do you have any dogs?
speaker1: no not yet but i do want one. Are Great Danes good dogs to have?
speaker2: They're really great dogs and I love mine, but their size can be a challenge, and they cost a lot because of how much they eat.  I feel mighty safe when I walk them though.
speaker1: yes i seen a couple of them and they are pretty big but they are cute. I may get a smaller dog though. not sure yet. Have you ever had a little dog? the ones that dont get real big

speaker2: Corgies are pretty small.  But I've not had anything really tiny like a chihuahua or anything like that.  They're definitely easier to take care of (usually), but I find something particularly attractive about big dogs.

speaker1: I will just have to look around some more because i just not sure what kind i really want. I see you love Mexican food so do i. I love me some authentic Mexican. What's your fav. Mexican dish?
speaker2: Other than fajitas I really like chimichangas, but I usually load mine up with hot sauce and jalapenos to up the spice level.  How about you?
speaker1: I love a good taco. and i loved mines with jalapenos
speaker2: Yes, tacos are a good fail-safe at most Mexican restaurants.  Do you like chicken, beef, shrimp, or what as your taco filling?
speaker1: I like all them but i usually do chicken. sometime i put them all together. What about you?

speaker2: Yes, I've done a sea-land-and-air taco once, with beef, chicken, and shrimp.  It's not my preferred way to eat tacos, but it was good.  Normally I do chicken as well, but beef is a close second.  Always with extra hot sauce.
speaker1: I saw this great small dog at the pound earlier! If I showed you a picture, would you tell me what you think of it? I am thinking of adopting it.
speaker2: Of course I would tell you what I think!! I love dogs.  I think thats a great idea to adopt!
speaker1: thank you! I'll send the picture later.  It's a shih tzu, I had one as a kid and I loved him.
speaker2: Maybe we can get our dogs together for a doggie play date after you adopt!!
speaker1: that sounds great! do they get along well with other dogs?
response: They definitely do.  Milos and Dante are large, but very gentle with smaller dogs and Buster is small and friendly as well!  We could always have mexican food for dinner while the dogs play!

speaker1: How are you and the kids doing lately?

speaker1: I'm really sorry to hear that, it must be terrible to go through! If you want, I'm free this weekend and can help take the kids off your hands for a little while. I can take them to go get ice cream and play at the park with my dog!

speaker1: That'd be perfect! I've been meaning to ask you for your meatball recipe, they're my favorite! Do you think we can have them for dinner and you could show me how to make them?
